{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/conduct-disorders-in-children-young-people/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"b3d876df-f88f-5e64-bcad-4652b5b0d949","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field adb0ef6c-1f6b-48ee-b695-c4b6cabf1cc3 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field adb0ef6c-1f6b-48ee-b695-c4b6cabf1cc3 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f45bca64-a827-4c30-8510-d5f07ee09841 --><!-- begin field 889723c7-d017-43c4-8d71-b80e31fdc54c --><p><strong>The term 'conduct disorders' is an overarching term used to describe conduct disorder and oppositional defiant disorder.</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Conduct disorder </strong>is a persistent (several months or longer) pattern of antisocial behaviour where a child or young person repeatedly carries out aggressive acts that may cause them distress and/or social impairment, and upset other people.<ul><li><strong>Examples of antisocial behaviours associated with conduct disorder include:</strong><ul><li>Fighting and/or bullying.</li><li>Cruelty to animals or people.</li><li>Destructiveness to property.</li><li>Setting fires.</li><li>Stealing.</li><li>Repeated lying.</li><li>Truancy from school.</li><li>Running away from home.</li><li>Unusually severe temper tantrums.</li><li>Defiant provocative behaviour.</li><li>Persistent severe disobedience.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Conduct disorders are usually diagnosed over the age of three years old</strong>. If antisocial behaviours occurs:<ul><li>Before 10 years of age, this is referred to as 'early onset'.</li><li>After 10 years of age, this is referred to as 'adolescent onset'.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Oppositional defiant disorder </strong>is a sub-type and milder variation of conduct disorder seen in younger children aged up to 10 years of age. Examples of antisocial behaviours associated with oppositional defiant disorder are:<ul><li>Often feeling angry, spiteful or resentful.</li><li>Annoying others and being easily annoyed.</li><li>Blaming others for mistakes or misbehaviour.</li><li>Ignoring or rebelling against rules, at home or at school.</li><li>Arguing with adults.</li><li>Unusually quick loss of temper.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/conduct-disorders-in-children-young-people/references/\">NICE, 2017a</a>] </p><!-- end field 889723c7-d017-43c4-8d71-b80e31fdc54c --><!-- end item f45bca64-a827-4c30-8510-d5f07ee09841 -->","topic":{"id":"5b431fd1-05a9-56a5-b500-9c93007db332","topicId":"0ee10521-7c63-43a1-9caa-cc3ffd1ae8ae","topicName":"Conduct disorders in children and young people","slug":"conduct-disorders-in-children-young-people","lastRevised":"Last revised in April 2018","chapters":[{"id":"ff86f455-780d-53a9-9fe8-3b13d33937f6","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"f57099d8-a1de-5af0-961c-998de57a0607","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"b2b660db-759d-589a-8af4-8e406dfde295","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"c46c3136-0235-56c1-95f3-33ba2238c3ee","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"efc85d78-d915-53e6-a9f5-a3237191a8b3","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"0f04120b-aafa-5186-b320-86f26df06f44","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"c3bc9749-c69a-558a-bb94-c3ffbe156e78","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"0c109dc8-a769-5aba-aa28-d96fb62f6244","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"94cbf52b-cf7a-5775-bea2-caacce3c2dc1","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"a2e81c30-2393-5eeb-951e-4a5427e2e279","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"4a55b93f-bf20-50da-87